textDelta: Lipoprotein lipase (LPL), a key enzyme in lipid metabolism, regulates the hydrolysis of triglycerides in chylomicrons, very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL), and low-density lipoproteins (LDL). LPL also plays a central role in reverse cholesterol transport, a process that removes excess cholesterol from peripheral tissues to the liver for excretion ([@b1]). Lipoprotein Liver-Targeted Drug Delivery System (LPDS): A Review. Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is one of the leading causes of cancer-related death worldwide. Lipoprotein liver-targeted drug delivery system (LPDS), as a novel drug delivery system, has been recently used for treatment of HCC. This review summarizes the current progress of LPDS, including preparation methods, characterization, pharmacokinetics, in vivo therapeutic efficacy, and toxicity. The advantages and disadvantages of LPDS are also discussed in this review.

Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions (SORT) SORT Treaty The Soviet Union and the United States signed the SORT treaty on 8 May 1991. The treaty came into effect on 5 June 1993. The SORT treaty was designed to stop the proliferation of nuclear weapons. It limited the number of deployed intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs), submarine-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs) and heavy bombers. The SORT treaty was superseded by the START treaty of 1991. The SORT treaty is also known as the Moscow Treaty.

Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive United States, Britain, and the Soviet Union signed this treaty on August 31, 1972. The treaty stated that neither nation would develop or test any ground-launched cruise missiles with a range greater than 300 miles. The treaty also called for the destruction of existing ground-launched cruise missiles. SALT II Treaty Signed by President Jimmy Carter and General Secretary Leonid Brezhnev on June 18, 1979, the treaty called for equal limits on strategic offensive weapons. Rising Income food expenditure and obesity: A decomposition analysis. Rising income, food expenditure and obesity are closely linked. However, the mechanisms through which this relationship operates remain poorly understood. This paper aims to decompose the contribution of changes in food expenditure to changes in obesity. Using data from the National Nutrition and Physical Activity Survey, we decompose changes in expenditure on food, non-alcoholic beverages and eating out by income group and by income group and by gender. We also examine whether the contribution of changes in food expenditure to changes in obesity differs by income group. We find that rising expenditure on food, non-alcoholic beverages and eating out contributes to rising obesity
